^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at| Before we continue the play, let me discuss why I led a trumps. There are some auctions where a trump lead is indicated, Typically they are where each opponent has bid another suit besides trump, and finally found a fit and you are either long or short in the opponents' other suits. This auction was one of those cases. moe bid diamonds, ira bid hearts, before they settled on spades and I was long in hearts and short in diamonds, so it looked to me like the hand might involve a cross ruff. That is why I led a trump.|
PG| ***** 111 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|People often lead trumps when they have nothing better to lead and sometimes that is ok. But a more important reason to lead trumps is when it sounds like there might be some ruffing going on, as on this hand. There is a danger to leading trumps, in that it can often give away a trick, by finessing partner so you need to be cautious when you lead them. Trump holdings that are especially dangerous to lead from are a singleton trump. |
PG| ***** 112 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Leading a singleton trump quite often gives away a trick, so I really tend to shy away from that lead, unless I know they have a 10 card fit. Another dangerous holding is 2 or 3 to the J or Q, e.g. Qxx Jxx Jx or Qx. Leading from those tends to give away a trick. But absent those holdings, if the auction calls for a trump lead, then leading one is good. Now, we can continue with the play|
