^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let us discuss the auction, as there are some interesting implications. First of all my reopening double is important. In the old days, people did not play negative doubles, so a double of 2@D by pam would have been for penalty. However, these days, everyone plays negative doubles (which is an excellent convention), so it is not possible to penalize the 2@D bid. That is, responder is no longer able to make a penatly double. Since penalty double hands come up much less frequently than negative double hands, that is usually not a big deal.|
PG| ***** 162 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, it does make it hard for responder to bid when they have the same suit as the overcaller. Therefore, opener must be aware of the possibility that responder may pass with a pretty good hand and the overcaller's suit and responder would really have liked to make a penalty double. So, if opener is short in the overcaller's suit, he should strain to double, in case responder wants to pass and that is what I did in this case.|
PG| ***** 163 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|pam should think seriously about passing. They are vulnerable. down 1 is probably a pretty good score. and down 2 is a great score. It turns out they are down 2. losing 3 spades, 2 diamonds, 1 heart and 1 club. My wife ava, who loves to penalize part scores, would have passed in a flash with pam's hand, lol. I am not sure I would. it is close. The other issue is now when pam bids 2N, I think she has a weakish hand with diamonds because if she had 10 or 11 points with diamonds, she should probably bid 2N over 2@D and that is why I passed her 2N bid.|
PG| ***** 164 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, pam, by failing to bid 2N the first time, and then bidding 2N the second time, you showed a weaker hand than what you had. Pam should have bid 2NT the first round or passed the penalty double, one of the two. We should either be in 3N or 2D doubled. But the important point here is to remember as opener, when there is an overcall, and you are short in the overcaller's suit, you should strain to reopen with a double, in case partner has a penalty pass.|
